    {
      "title": "Parallel Reactions",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Studying Different Types Of Reactions</strong></h3><p><strong>Parallel (or Simultaneous) Reactions</strong></p><p>Reactions in which two products are formed from same set of reactant(s) by different paths are called parallel or simultaneous. For example,$\\alpha -\\text{D}-$ glucose and $\\beta -\\text{D}-\\text{glucose}$ are formed in solution from the aldehydic form of $\\text{D}$-glucose following different paths as:</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"433\" height=\"145\"></p><p>The various differential rate laws are</p><p>$-\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{A}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]+{{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{A}]=\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}+{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)[\\text{A}]$ … (a)</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]$ … (b)</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{C}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{A}]$ … (c)</p><p>Now, let us assume that at $t=0$, only A was present. After a very small time, let us say, 2 second, $\\text{x}$ mole/l of $\\text{B}$ and $\\text{y}$ mole/l of $\\text{C}$ was formed.</p><p>Then $\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}=\\frac{\\text{x}}{2}\\text{ and }\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{C}]}{\\text{dt}}=\\frac{\\text{y}}{2}$</p><p>$\\frac{\\frac{d[B]}{dt}}{\\frac{d[C]}{dt}}=\\frac{x}{y}$</p><p>From equation (b) and (c)</p><p>$\\frac{\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}}{\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{C}]}{\\text{dt}}}=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}$</p><p>$\\therefore $ $\\frac{\\text{x}}{\\text{y}}=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}$</p><p>This means that at any given instant of time, the ratio of amount of $\\text{B}$ formed to that of $\\text{C}$ formed till that instant is a constant.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dc3fc03b9dcaf1afe57d"
    },
