      "title": "Sequential reactions",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>&nbsp;Sequential reactions</strong></h3><p>Suppose that we have two sequential reactions which for simplicity we will assume are both first order.</p><p>$\\text{A}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{1}}}\\text{B}[\\text{1}]$</p><p>$\\text{B}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{2}}}\\text{C}[\\text{2}]$</p><p>We can imagine two extreme (limiting) cases:</p><p>(1) Rate constant of process [1] is very much greater than that of process [2]:</p><p>${{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\gg {{\\text{k}}_{2}}$</p><p>In this case $\\text{A}i$ converted rapidly into $\\text{B}$, leading to an accumulation of $\\text{B}$ which is more slowly converted into $\\text{C}$. The rate at which the product $\\text{C}$ is formed depends on the rate of process [2] - it is said that step [2] is the rate determining step.</p><p>(2) Rate constant of process [2] is very much greater than that of process [1].</p><p>${{\\text{k}}_{2}}&gt;{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{. }$</p><p>In this case $\\text{A}$ is converted slowly into $\\text{B}$, and then $\\text{B}$ reacts to form $\\text{C}$ almost as soon as $\\text{B}$ is formed. The rate at which the product $\\text{C}$ is formed depends on the rate of process [1] - step [1] is now the rate determining step. In this limit there is very little B present at any time as the moment it is produced it reacts.</p><p>If either of these limiting cases applies then the kinetics is greatly simplified, as the overall rate of production of the product depends only on the step with the smallest rate constant. The same is true for more complex schemes of sequential reactions.</p><p>$\\text{A}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{1}}}\\text{B}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{2}}}\\text{C}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{3}}}\\text{D}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{4}}}\\text{E}$</p><p>If the step from $\\text{B}$ to $\\text{C}$ has the smallest rate constant, then the rate of formation of the product $\\text{E}$ depends only on ${{\\text{k}}_{2}}$.</p><p>$\\text{A}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{1}}}\\text{B}\\xrightarrow{{{K}_{2}}}\\text{C}$</p><p>The differential rate equations are</p><p>Rate of disappearance of A, $\\frac{-\\text{d}[\\text{A}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]$ … (a)</p><p>Rate of change of B, $\\frac{d[B]}{dt}={{k}_{1}}[A]-{{k}_{2}}[B]$ … (b)</p><p>Rate of formation of C, $\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{C}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]$ … (c)</p><p>Integrating equation (a) within the limits we get,</p><p>${{[\\text{A}]}_{\\text{t}}}={{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}{{\\text{e}}^{-\\text{k},\\text{t}}}$ … (d)</p><p>In order to get the value of B at any instant of time, we need to integrate equation (b). Since this is a differentia equation, we integrate it in the following manner.</p><p>First bringing${{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]$ to the left side of the equation</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}+{{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]={{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]$ … (e)</p><p>From equation (8e), we get</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}+{{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]={{\\text{k}}_{1}}{{[~\\text{A}]}_{0}}{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{t}}}$</p><p>Integration of this equation is not possible as we are unable to separate the two variables, $[\\text{B}]$ and t. Thus, the equation is to multiplied on both sides by an integrating factor ${{e}^{k2t}}$.</p><p>${{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}\\left( \\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}+{{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}] \\right)={{\\text{k}}_{1}}{{[~\\text{A}]}_{0}}{{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)t}}$</p><p>${{e}^{{{k}_{2}}t}}\\frac{d[B]}{dt}+{{k}_{2}}[B]{{e}^{{{k}_{2}}t}}={{k}_{1}}{{[A]}_{0}}{{e}^{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)t}}$ … (f)</p><p>Left hand side of the equation (f) is equal to $\\frac{d}{dt}\\left( [B]{{e}^{{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right)$(a differential of $[B]{{e}_{k2t}}$)</p><p>$\\frac{d}{dt}\\left( [B]{{e}^{{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right)={{k}_{1}}{{[A]}_{0}}{{e}^{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)t}}$</p><p>$\\text{d}\\left( [\\text{B}]{{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}} \\right)={{\\text{k}}_{1}}{{[~\\text{A}]}_{0}}{{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}}\\text{dt}$ … (g)</p><p>Integrating equation (g) within the limits, 0 and t,</p><p>$\\int_{0}^{[\\text{B}]{{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}\\text{d}}{\\text{d}}\\left( [\\text{B}]{{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}} \\right)={{\\text{k}}_{1}}{{[~\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\int_{0}^{\\text{t}}{\\text{e}}\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{tdt}$</p><p>$[\\text{B}]{{\\text{e}}^{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}={{\\text{k}}_{1}}{{[~\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ \\frac{{{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{t}}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right]_{0}^{\\text{t}}=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ {{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{t}}}-1 \\right]$</p><p>$[B]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}\\left[ {{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)\\text{t}}}-1 \\right]$</p><p>$[B]=\\frac{k}{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{[A]}_{0}}\\left[ {{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}-{{e}^{-{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right]$ … (8h)</p><p>In general, the concentration of A decreases exponentially, the concentration of B initially increases up to a maximum and then decreases thereafter, and the concentration of $\\text{C}$ increases steadily.</p><p><strong>Time when $\\mathbf{[B]}$ becomes maximum&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{B}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]=0$</p><p>${{\\text{k}}_{1}}[~\\text{A}]={{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]$</p><p>Substituting equation (8d) and equation (8h), we get</p><p>${{k}_{1}}{{[A]}_{0}}{{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}=\\frac{{{k}_{2}}{{k}_{1}}}{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{[A]}_{0}}\\left[ {{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}-{{e}^{-{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right]$</p><p>Rearranging, we get</p><p>$\\frac{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{{k}_{2}}}=\\frac{\\left[ {{e}^{-{{K}_{1}}t}}-e{{-}^{{{K}_{2}}t}} \\right]}{{{e}^{-{{K}_{1}}t}}}$</p><p>$1-\\frac{{{k}_{1}}}{{{k}_{2}}}=1-{{e}^{\\left( {{k}_{1}}-{{k}_{2}} \\right)t}}$</p><p>${{t}_{\\text{max }}}=\\frac{1}{\\left( {{k}_{1}}-{{k}_{2}} \\right)}\\ln \\frac{{{k}_{1}}}{{{k}_{2}}}$ … (8i)</p><p><strong>Maximum concentration of $\\mathbf{B}$</strong></p><p>$[B]=\\frac{{{k}_{1}}}{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{[A]}_{0}}\\left[ {{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}-{{e}^{-{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right]$</p><p>$[\\text{B}]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ \\frac{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}}\\frac{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{-{{\\text{e}}^{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}}\\text{ln}\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}} \\right]$</p><p>$[\\text{B}]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}$$\\left[ {{\\text{e}}^{\\ln \\left( \\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}}-{{\\text{e}}^{\\ln \\left( \\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}} \\right]$</p><p>${{[\\text{B}]}_{\\max }}=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ {{\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)}^{\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}}-{{\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)}^{\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{1}}-{{\\text{k}}_{2}} \\right)}}} \\right]$ … (j)</p><p>In order to get the concentration of $[\\text{C}]$, we substitute $[\\text{B}]$ equation $(8~\\text{h})$ to $(8\\text{c})$ and then integrate within the limits.</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}[\\text{C}]}{\\text{dt}}={{\\text{k}}_{2}}[~\\text{B}]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ {{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{t}}}-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}} \\right]$</p><p>$\\text{d}[\\text{C}]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ \\text{e}-{{-}^{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{t}}}-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}} \\right]\\text{dt}$</p><p>Upon integrating within the limits, 0 to t,</p><p>$\\int_{0}^{[C]}{d}[C]=\\frac{{{k}_{2}}{{k}_{1}}}{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{[A]}_{0}}\\int_{0}^{t}{\\left[ {{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}-{{e}^{-{{k}_{2}}t}} \\right]}dt$</p><p>$[C]=\\frac{{{k}_{2}}{{k}_{1}}}{\\left( {{k}_{2}}-{{k}_{1}} \\right)}{{[A]}_{0}}\\left[ \\frac{{{e}^{-{{k}_{1}}t}}}{-{{k}_{1}}}-\\frac{{{e}^{-{{k}_{2}}t}}}{-{{k}_{2}}} \\right]_{0}^{t}$</p><p>$[C]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ \\left( \\frac{{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{t}}}-1}{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)-\\left( \\frac{{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}-1}{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}} \\right) \\right]$</p><p>$[\\text{C}]=\\frac{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}{{\\text{k}}_{1}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}\\left[ \\left( \\frac{1-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\text{t}}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{1}}} \\right)-\\left( \\frac{1-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}}}{{{\\text{k}}_{2}}} \\right) \\right]$</p><p>$[\\text{C}]=\\frac{{{[\\text{A}]}_{0}}}{\\left( {{\\text{k}}_{2}}-{{\\text{k}}_{1}} \\right)}\\left[ {{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\left( 1-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{\\text{t}}}\\text{t}}} \\right)-{{\\text{k}}_{1}}\\left( 1-{{\\text{e}}^{-{{\\text{k}}_{2}}\\text{t}}} \\right) \\right]$ … (k)</p>",
